Getting started with Acacia¶

The MinIO client is the preferred supported client for Acacia, however the Rclone client has some advantages. It is better to be comfortable with both clients and use the strengths of each. For power usage of Acacia you may want to look at the AWS command line interface or the AWS boto3 library to use Acacia from Python.

In this tutorial we are going to explore:

  • Getting help
  • Working with buckets
    • Creating, listing, and removing buckets
  • Working with files and metadata
    • Copying simple files
    • Copying mutiple files
    • Adding and extracting metadata
    • Constructing URL's for download and upload
    • Removing objects
    • Synchronising directories to Acacia

Getting help for MinIO and Rclone¶

The complete guide to MinIO client commands is here, and the complete guide to Rclone commands is here. To get help from MinIO client use this command

mc --help

And to get help on a particular command use this

mc command --help

Rclone has a similar syntax

rclone --help

rclone command --help

Exercise: Lookup help on the "mb" command with mc, and the "mkdir" command with rclone

Buckets as storage containers¶

Buckets are basic containers for grouping objects. There is no concept of a sub-bucket, so the similarity to a folder ends there!

Important information¶

On Acacia:

  • A user or project may each have up to 1000 buckets.
  • Up to a million objects may be in a bucket (less than 100,000 preferred).
  • A user has 100GB of personal storage
  • Projects are given 1TB of storage by default

The bucket name:

  • Must be unique across the system!
  • Bucket names can potentially be made public using links. Therefore bucket names must not contain any confidential information
    • Usernames can be a target for an attack
    • Email addresses can be exploited
    • Passwords and secret keys obviously not ok!
    • Initials are ok if they aren't a Pawsey username
  • Must be 3-63 characters long
  • Must begin and end with a lowercase letter or a digit
  • May contain lowercase letters, numbers, hyphens (-) and periods (.)
  • Must not be formatted as an IP address (e.g 192.168.0.5), that would be problematic for uniqueness!

One way to create a unique bucket name is to incorporate something related to your work, i.e the project name. For example this is a valid bucket name.

courses01-acacia-workshop-2022

Creating buckets¶

Here is the mc command to create a bucket. Don't forget the alias!

mc mb acacia-mine/<bucket_name>

or

rclone mkdir acacia-mine:<bucket_name>

With mc if you get the name of the alias wrong it will start making files and directories on your local filesystem! Tab completion will help avoid this, or use Rclone doesn't have this vulnerability.

Once a bucket is created it may not be renamed. The fallback is to then to make a new bucket and transfer objects between them.

Exercise: Come up with a unique bucket name and make your own bucket on Acacia.

There might even be a clash as your colleagues might make the same bucket name!

Listing available buckets and objects¶

The ls command lists available buckets and objects

mc ls acacia-mine

And if you want to list all objects as well you can do this.

mc ls --recursive acacia-mine

With Rclone there are a few options for listing buckets and their contents:

  • ls lists objects only, lsl gives more information
  • lsd lists buckets and pseudofolders
  • lsf lists objects and buckets in easy to parse format
  • lsjson lists objects and buckets in JSON format
rclone lsd acacia-mine:

rclone lsf acacia-mine:

Removing buckets¶

You can remove buckets with this command.

mc rb acacia-mine/<bucket_name>

or

rclone rmdir acacia-mine:<bucket_name>

If the bucket contains objects and you want to delete everything in it then you can force a remove with this command.

mc rb --force acacia-mine/<bucket_name>

or

rclone purge acacia-mine:<bucket_name>

As this command is dangerous both programs support the --dry-run option to perform a non-destructive test run. The Rclone help messages say that all flags come after the destination.

rclone purge acacia-mine:<bucket_name> --dry-run

Exercise: Using one of the commands above, remove your bucket and make a new one.

Mock data¶

Now we can start working with data using MinIO client and Rclone. If you haven't already prepared the mock data, then follow the instructions at T1_Getting_Access -> L5_Mock_data to unpack the mock data for working with Acacia.

In the command line change directory to data -> simulation -> results. On Windows this is

cd C:\path\to\acacia_training\data\simulation\results

On Linux and MacOS change directory to the simulation directory using something like this:

cd /path/to/acacia_training/data/simulation/results

Working with files as objects¶

An object is a file that is uploaded to the data store.

Limits¶

There is no minimum or maximum limit on the size of objects that can be uploaded to Acacia. Only the number of objects per bucket (1 million max, 100,000 preferred) and allowed storage are limits.

The object name:

  • Must be unique within a bucket.
  • May contain alpha-numeric characters
    • 0-9
    • A-Z
    • a-z
  • May also contain these special characters:
    • Forward slash ( / )
    • Exclamation point ( ! )
    • Hyphen ( - )
    • Period ( . )
    • Asterisk ( * )
    • Single quote (')
    • Open and close parentheses (())

Copy a file to the object store¶

Simple copies to Acacia¶

The MinIO client has Unix-like commands for file operations. The cp command is used to copy data to Acacia.

mc cp data_00.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/

MinIO client always shows a progress bar while it is copying data. Rclone doesn't show it by default but you can enable it with the --progress option.

rclone copy data_00.dat acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/ --progress

A difference between rclone and mc is that mc will always naively copy the file again, whereas rclone works more like rsync and only copies if the size or the modification time have changed.

Exercise: Make another bucket and copy the file again to the new bucket.

In [ ]:

This shows that different buckets can have the same object name.

Simple copies from Acacia¶

We can copy a single file from Acacia to your system in much the same way.

mc cp acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat .

or

rclone copy acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/data_00.dat .

Pseudofolders¶

All storage within a bucket is flat storage, however when working with Acacia using mc and rclone we can prepend any number of pseudofolders (separated by a forward slash) to the name of the object in order to keep file names unique. In this instance we use the pseudofolder test. Notice that we don't need to make the test pseudofolder beforehand.

mc cp data_00.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/test/

rclone copy data_00.dat acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/ --progress

rclone ls acacia-mine:<bucket_name>

In such instances the text test/ is pre-pended to the name of the object. In a similar manner we can use the pseudofolder when copying back from object storage.

mc cp acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/test/data_00.dat .

rclone copy acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/data_00.dat . --progress

Copies with checksums¶

Both mc and rclone can be requested to use md5 checksums to copy data.

mc cp --md5 data_00.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>

or

rclone copy data_00.dat acacia-mine:<bucket_name> --checksum --progress

Copy multiple files by selection¶

When copying multiple files from Unix you can use regular expressions to copy a number of files to Acacia.

mc cp data_0*.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>

But on the return journey there doesn't appear to be an equivalent way of selecting multiple files using regular expressions. This is where rclone is helpful. You can't send multiple filenames to rclone, but you can use the --include option to select files using some common regular expressions. See this page for more information.

# Copy to Acacia, don't forget the dot .
rclone copy . acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/ --include "data_0*.dat" --progress

# Copy from Acacia, don't forget the dot .
rclone copy acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/ . --include "data_0*.dat" --progress

Working with metadata¶

Acacia has the ability to associate metadata with objects in the form of key:value pairs. This is very useful because the right metadata might save an expensive retrieval operation.

For example, we have two key:value pairs that we would like to associate with objects uploaded to our bucket

"island": "Rottnest"
"season" : "winter"

Adding metadata¶

MinIO client is easier to use when working with metadata. The option --attr alows us to specify metadata for use with mc.

# Note that attributes are
mc cp --attr "<key>=<value>;<key>=<value>" data_00.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/

for our example data above this is

# Note that attributes are
mc cp --attr "island=Rottnest;season=winter" data_00.dat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/

With rclone, uploading metadata is slightly more complex, the key:value pairs are part of a http header entry whose name is prefixed by X-Amz-Meta-. Each key:value pair must have it's own --header option.

rclone copy data_00.dat acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/ --header "X-Amz-Meta-<key>: <value>" --header "X-Amz-Meta-<key>: <value>"

for our example above, this is

rclone copy data_00.dat acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/ --header "X-Amz-Meta-island: Rottnest" --header "X-Amz-Meta-season: winter"

Note: Metadata is only created when an object is created. This is rather disappointing. With rclone, if a file is already on the object store then the above command will not update the metadata :-( In such instances the only way I can see to update the metadata is to use the option --no-check-dest which will upload the data again.

Extracting metadata¶

MinIO client uses the stat command to download the metadata.

mc stat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat

If we look at the output we see something like this

Name      : data_00.dat
Date      : 2022-06-10 15:40:04 AWST 
Size      : 977 KiB 
ETag      : 879f4bba57ed37c9ec5e5aedf9864698 
Type      : file 
Metadata  :
  X-Amz-Meta-Mtime : 1654843942 
  X-Amz-Meta-Season: winter 
  X-Amz-Meta-Island: Rottnest 
  Content-Type     : application/octet-stream

The metadata is located in the Metadata tags starting with X-Amz-Meta-. The ETag field contains the md5 checksum of the object. It is useful for verifying the contents of a file. We can add the --json flag to output the metadata in JSON format.

mc stat acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat --json

{
 "status": "success",
 "name": "data_01.dat",
 "lastModified": "2022-06-10T16:29:36+08:00",
 "size": 1000000,
 "etag": "879f4bba57ed37c9ec5e5aedf9864698",
 "type": "file",
 "metadata": {
  "Content-Type": "application/octet-stream",
  "X-Amz-Meta-Island": "Rottnest",
  "X-Amz-Meta-Mtime": "1654678836",
  "X-Amz-Meta-Season": "winter"
 }
}

Constructing URL's for sharing your data¶

Creating a download link¶

Sometimes you need to share data with someone else. Rclone supports the creation of a publicly accessible link using the command

mc share download acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat

and for rclone

rclone link acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/data_00.dat --expire 1d

From what I see the maximum time allowed for a valid link is a week. You can use the --expire option to set a shorter duration.

Creating an upload link¶

MinIO client has the additional ability to generate an upload link for use with curl.

mc share upload acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat

Exercise: create your own download link to the file data_00.dat

Test the link by downloading the file with a web browser.

Removing objects¶

In addition to the brute force bucket removal options, both mc and rclone have the ability to remove individual objects.

Simple removal¶

If you just need to delete one file here are the commands

mc rm acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_00.dat

or

rclone delete acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/data_00.dat

Removal of more than one file¶

MinIO is a little blunt when it comes to selecting specific files for deletion. If you use the --recursive and --force options you can use a prefix to select multiple files. In this instance we select anything that starts with data_

mc rm --recursive --force acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/data_

Rclone has much better filters to select objects when deleting. Just use the --include option and you can do regular expression style pattern matching.

rclone delete acacia-mine:<bucket_name> --include "data_*.dat"

Exercise: use one of the delete commands above to remove all .dat files from your test bucket

Sync a directory¶

Object storage is indeed flat within a bucket, however we can replicate a directory structure using pseudofolders. Both mc and rclone have the ability to recursively synchronise a directory to the object store, however recent Pawsey experience suggests that rclone is a more robust tool for this task.

In your terminal use the cd command to change directory to data, the one above simulation. We are going to synchronise the contents of the simulation directory to an acacia bucket and prepend test to object names so that the contents of simulation appear to be in the test pseudofolder.

mc mirror simulation acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/test

Note there is no forward slash (/) at the end with this command!! If one is placed there then for some strange reason it prepends a forward slash to the start of the object name! Rclone can't seem to delete the objects made in this way, but mc can.

Parallel transfers¶

Rclone doesn't make this error, we can also specify how many transfers to perform in parallel with the --transfers flag.

rclone sync simulation acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/ --progress --transfers 12

The Pawsey team recommends --transfers 12 to get the best performance.

Excluding files¶

You may also use multiple --exclude options with both commands to exclude certain files based on regular expressions.

mc mirror --exclude "*.log" simulation acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/test

or

rclone sync simulation acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/ --progress --exclude "*.log"

Checksums for verified copies¶

As with the copy command, both mc and rclone have option of using md5 checksums to ensure data consistency.

mc mirror --md5 simulation acacia-mine/<bucket_name>/test

or

rclone sync simulation acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/ --progress --transfers 12 --checksum

You can also use the check command with rclone to check a directory of files

rclone check simulation acacia-mine:<bucket_name>/test/ --checksum --combined report.txt

Exercise: use rclone to mirror the simulation directory to your chosen bucket name.¶

Feel free to use the --exclude options to omit for example the log files.

Note: empty directories can't be represented directly on the object store. If you need that functionality then use tar to preserve file and directory structures. Try creating an empty directory in simulation and see if it is replicated to Acacia.

Checking numbers of objects¶

From time to time you might need to count the number of objects in a bucket. You can either do this at the portal then click on ACACIA and then your storage access.

Alternatively, you can use the rclone size command to tally the number of objects in a bucket.

rclone size acacia-mine:<bucket_name>

Clean up¶

You really don't want your test buckets taking up space. Purge with with the following commands

rclone purge acacia-mine:<bucket_name>
